{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"01b67076-86e8-482c-b854-7c537201d908","content":"Good news — in .NET 10, `dotnet test` uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform **by default**. You **no longer need `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`** — that was the .NET 9 opt-in bridge. It's now implicit.\n\nYou can simplify your `.csproj` by removing that property:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_019RfgajsNUrSdNVqZik59Rt","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-e53f57c7034f4e4cb77b1fe1140f3d32/TestProject.csproj","old_str":"    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>","new_str":"    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-e53f57c7034f4e4cb77b1fe1140f3d32/TestProject.csproj."}],"interactionId":"bf78c8d9-c503-4b38-8e3d-d75e70e742b8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is on .NET 10 SDK (10.0.100) and using MSTest with `EnableMSTestRunner` and `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` set to true.\n\nIn .NET 10, `dotnet test` natively uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) as the default test runner. The `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` property was needed in .NET 9 to opt into MTP support with `dotnet test`, but in .NET 10 it's no longer needed because MTP is the default.\n\nLet me provide accurate guidance:\n\n1. In .NET 10, `dotnet test` uses MTP by default — no need for `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`.\n\n\n2. `EnableMSTestRunner` is still required to make the test project an executable that runs on MTP.\n3. They can safely remove `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` since it's now implicit in .NET 10.\n\nThe `OutputType` of `Exe` is set because `EnableMSTestRunner` requires the test project to be a self-contained executable, though MSTest 3.8+ may handle this automatically.\n\nNow I'll put together the final answer with the updated project file.","outputTokens":633,"requestId":"0BD6:33AAFA:250E97:2B